<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title><%= title %></title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css" />
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="bg"></div>

    <header class="container header">
      <div>
        <div class="kicker">Express + EJS</div>
        <h1 class="title"><%= title %></h1>
        <p class="sub">
          A simple home page for practicing <span class="pill">multiple servers</span> behind
          <span class="pill">Nginx reverse proxy</span> on AWS.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="badge">
        <div class="badge-top">Server</div>
        <div class="badge-main"><%= serverName %></div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <main class="container grid">
      <section class="card">
        <h2>Request details</h2>
        <div class="kv">
          <div class="k">Host</div>
          <div class="v"><%= host %></div>
          <div class="k">PORT</div>
          <div class="v"><%= port %></div>
          <div class="k">Time (ISO)</div>
          <div class="v"><%= now %></div>
        </div>

        <div class="muted small">
          Tip: set <code>SERVER_NAME</code> differently per instance so you can see which upstream answered.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2>Proxy headers (from Nginx)</h2>
        <div class="kv">
          <div class="k">X-Request-Id</div>
          <div class="v"><%= requestId ? requestId : "—" %></div>
          <div class="k">X-Forwarded-For</div>
          <div class="v"><%= forwardedFor ? forwardedFor : "—" %></div>
        </div>

        <div class="muted small">
          If these show up, it means Nginx is forwarding headers correctly to your Node app.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="card">
        <h2>Cross-server demo</h2>
        <p class="muted">
          Fetch JSON from <span class="pill">api-server</span> and render it here via EJS:
        </p>
        <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
          <a class="pill" href="/api">Open API Data →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="muted small" style="margin-top: 10px;">
          If this works, your two servers are connected and data is transitioning correctly.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="card wide">
        <h2>Suggested Nginx upstream test</h2>
        <p class="muted">
          Run two Node servers on different ports, then load-balance with Nginx. Example idea:
        </p>
        <pre class="code"><code>upstream app {
  server 127.0.0.1:3000;
  server 127.0.0.1:3001;
}

server {
  listen 80;
  location / {
    proxy_set_header Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    proxy_set_header X-Request-Id $request_id;
    proxy_pass http://app;
  }
}</code></pre>
      </section>
    </main>

    <footer class="container footer">
      <span>Made with EJS •</span>
      <span class="muted">Edit <code>views/home.ejs</code> and <code>public/styles.css</code></span>
    </footer>
  </body>
</html>


